<h1><strong><em>Areas of Similar Figures</em></strong></h1>
</div>
<p>Earlier in this module, it was stated that if the linear units have a ra=
tio of <img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://spscc.pressbooks.pub/app/uplo=
ads/quicklatex/quicklatex.com-69a7c7fb1023d315f416440bca10d849_l3.svg" clas=
s=3D"ql-img-inline-formula quicklatex-auto-format" alt=3D"1" title=3D"Rende=
red by QuickLaTeX.com" height=3D"12" width=3D"7" style=3D"vertical-align: 0=
px;"> to <img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://spscc.pres=
sbooks.pub/app/uploads/quicklatex/quicklatex.com-ec4217f4fa5fcd92a9edceba0e=
708cf7_l3.svg" class=3D"ql-img-inline-formula quicklatex-auto-format" alt=
=3D"n" title=3D"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com" height=3D"8" width=3D"11" style=
=3D"vertical-align: 0px;">, the square units will have a ratio of <img deco=
ding=3D"async" src=3D"https://spscc.pressbooks.pub/app/uploads/quicklatex/q=
uicklatex.com-69a7c7fb1023d315f416440bca10d849_l3.svg" class=3D"ql-img-inli=
ne-formula quicklatex-auto-format" alt=3D"1" title=3D"Rendered by QuickLaTe=
X.com" height=3D"12" width=3D"7" style=3D"vertical-align: 0px;"> to <img lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://spscc.pressbooks.pub/app/u=
ploads/quicklatex/quicklatex.com-e88489b836d3ea4c1e2c8d1f5576ce86_l3.svg" c=
lass=3D"ql-img-inline-formula quicklatex-auto-format" alt=3D"n^2" title=3D"=
Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com" height=3D"15" width=3D"18" style=3D"vertical-al=
ign: 0px;">. This applies to similar figures as well.</p>
<div class=3D"textbox shaded">If the linear dimensions of two similar figur=
es have a ratio of <img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://spscc.pressbooks.=
pub/app/uploads/quicklatex/quicklatex.com-69a7c7fb1023d315f416440bca10d849_=
l3.svg" class=3D"ql-img-inline-formula quicklatex-auto-format" alt=3D"1" ti=
tle=3D"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com" height=3D"12" width=3D"7" style=3D"verti=
cal-align: 0px;"> to <img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https:=
//spscc.pressbooks.pub/app/uploads/quicklatex/quicklatex.com-ec4217f4fa5fcd=
92a9edceba0e708cf7_l3.svg" class=3D"ql-img-inline-formula quicklatex-auto-f=
ormat" alt=3D"n" title=3D"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com" height=3D"8" width=3D=
"11" style=3D"vertical-align: 0px;">, then the areas will have a ratio of <=
img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://spscc.pressbooks.pub/app/uploads/quic=
klatex/quicklatex.com-69a7c7fb1023d315f416440bca10d849_l3.svg" class=3D"ql-=
img-inline-formula quicklatex-auto-format" alt=3D"1" title=3D"Rendered by Q=
uickLaTeX.com" height=3D"12" width=3D"7" style=3D"vertical-align: 0px;"> to=
 <img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://spscc.pressbooks.p=
ub/app/uploads/quicklatex/quicklatex.com-e88489b836d3ea4c1e2c8d1f5576ce86_l=
3.svg" class=3D"ql-img-inline-formula quicklatex-auto-format" alt=3D"n^2" t=
itle=3D"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com" height=3D"15" width=3D"18" style=3D"ver=
tical-align: 0px;">.</div>
<p>This is true for circles, similar triangles, similar rectangles, similar=
 hexagons, you name it. We=E2=80=99ll verify this in the following exercise=
s.</p>
<div class=3D"textbox textbox--exercises">
